title: For Sale:  Para Ordnance P14-45 1911 + Mags & Spare Parts
postcontent: I have decided to part ways with my Para P14-45, as I haven't used it in quite some time. This is one of Para's double-stack 1911 pistols; 14-round mags of .45ACP. This gun is a pleasure to shoot. I am the 2nd owner (I believe), and have always kept it clean and in my safe when not in use (it was never a carry pistol of mine, so no holster wear to speak of). This pistol has the factory match-grade barrel and the fiber optic sights. I couldn't find the exact production year based on the serial number, but there is a shipping sticker still on the case that shows a ship date of November 8, 2012 (so I would guess a 2011-2012 model)I have a couple of aftermarket parts currently installed on the pistol: A set of Hogue rubber wraparound grips, a Fusion Firearms silver checkered extended mag catch, and Wolff +10% power springs in both of the factory mags. I had intended at one point to deck this out with brushed nickel accessories, but never quite finished the build, so all of those parts are included. The following parts will be included with the pistol:- One additional Wolff +10% power mag spring- One Wolff 18.5# recoil spring- Two Wolff hammer springs- One JTM brushed nickel trigger- One Guncraft SS mag release- One Wilson Combat SS extended slide release- One MecGar 14-round magazine- One USA Magazines 14-round magazine- Factory case/boxAdditionally, the two factory Para mags are included, as well as the factory grips and mag catch that were replaced. These double-stack 1911's are becoming rarer to find these days, and I wanted to have spares of all of the doublestack-specific parts on hand. Any other part on this gun can be replaced with standard 1911 parts, with the exception of the magazines, trigger, and mag catch, so I have backups of all of those.This particular model does have a history of feeding issues. Full disclosure: This does happen occasionally on this pistol, depending on how you are gripping it while firing. There are numerous articles available that describe fixes for this issue, and I have all of the parts that are needed, I just never had the time to test the different spring/magazine combinations to find the ideal combo. A day at the range experimenting with different spring combos would probably do the trick, or worst-case scenario, it may need the barrel feed ramp polished.Please e-mail or text REDACTED) with questions. Additional pictures available upon request.
